  "summary": "Frankie begins investigating the Baskington-French family to uncover their connections. She consults her father, the Earl of Marchmont, who provides details on the family's various branches: a Shropshire branch facing financial difficulties due to inheritance taxes, a branch in Ireland, and a Hampshire branch linked to a wealthy American heiress.\n\nSeeking more information on the man suspected of being near the scene of the crime, Frankie visits the real estate agency Wheeler and Owen. Mr. Owen reports that a Mr. Baskington-French had inquired about property, visiting the agency on a Tuesday around 6:30 PM—the same day the man fell from the cliff. According to Owen, the man stayed with the deceased until the police arrived, but Frankie remains skeptical of his motives, noting that he returned to London the very next day.\n\nFrankie then visits Inspector Williams at the police station to clarify details regarding the deceased, Prichard. The inspector contradicts previous rumors of spy materials or drugs, stating that Prichard's pockets contained only a handkerchief, change, cigarettes, and treasury bills, along with a single photograph of his sister. Finally, Frankie inquires about the poisoning of the priest's son. The inspector reveals that a deep blue Talbot with the license plate GG8282 was observed near the scene of the cliff fall, a vehicle belonging to the bishop of St. Botolph's Church.",
